{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:05:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:05:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1898"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0,0.72,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1898"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"559"},{"type":"tags","id":"1212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"7331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice having difficulties with his right hand. He states \u0022Suddenly I just drop things \u0022. One month prior to this presentation he fell through a window with his hand, causing a laceration that has since healed. He shows his hands (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures has been damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right extensor digitorum indicis","Left extensor digitorum indicis","Right abductor pollicis longus","Left abductor pollicis longus","Left abductor pollicis brevis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOne month earlier the patient had fallen through a window and sustained a laceration to the base of his right thumb. He is now unable to abduct that thumb. The prime action of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabductor pollicis longus\u003C/strong\u003E is movement of the thumb anteriorly. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETogether with the \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor pollicis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E, the abductor pollicis longus is responsible for the extension and rotation of the thumb. This muscle is inserted into the base of the first metacarpal bone - this is the site where the laceration occurred in this patient. On examination, there appears to be an absent tendon protrusion on the right thumb, compared to the left. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor digitorium\u003C/strong\u003E indices allow for the extension of the 5th digit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abductor pollicus longus allows for abduction and extension of the thumb and inserts at the base of the 1st metacarpal"],"references":["Jenkins DB. Hollinshead\u0027s Functional Anatomy of the Limbs and Back, 8th ed, Saunders, Philadelphia 2002.","Moore KL, Dalley AF II. Clincally Oriented Anatomy, 5th ed, Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, Philadelphia 2006."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14970"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14970"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/st